message:
Hi Stephen,   
Great article, helped me very much! I found this article  
 because you have linked it in one of your answers on stack overflow. In  
 this post you mention  
"I don't recommend wrapping an entire method in Task.Run".

I  
 have some methods (in a class library) that I must be able to call from  
 a winforms application as well as from a console applition. The methods  
 take some time, have to be executed in the background, must report   
progress or reqest user interaction and support cancellation.   
All that would be possible with the Task.Run(), but I would have to call for example:

private async void btnStart_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)  
{  
 //Init progress handler, cancellation token, wrap in try catch statement according to you article  
 // ...

 await Task.Run(() =>  
 {  
 someClass.LongRunningFunction(progressHandler);  
 });

 //Evaluate Cancel, Error, etc.   
}

If  
 I understand your post on stack overflow, this would be a bad   
implementation (as an entire method is wrapped in Task.Run), but I don't  
 really understand where there are possible problems, and even more   
important, can you give me hint on a better implementation technique?

Thanks in advance!
